<Author>Marrakechlover
<Content>Don't overlook this hotel My fiancee and I spent 6 nights here, and would absolutely stay here again.The noise from the Zocalo is everything that people say it is, to say nothing of the church bells and midddle-of-the-night nearby building alarms, but all in all, the experience was superb. If you stay in room 604 you will find a very firm kingsize bed, with a gorgeous arched window looking out over the main church on the square: it is a view that will stay with us forever. The coffee that they serve at breakfast is often lukewarm, at best, but we found a very simple solution: simply tell your waiter that you want cafe muy caliente - in which case they will generally bring you piping hot coffee. The breakfast buffet is superb, and the steaks for dinner are also excellent quality (even if very thing by American steak house standards). The margaritas were varied, but we found a solution to this problem as well: we snuck our own tequila into them, and added lime which they served at the table anyway. The 7th floor terrace restaurant is the place to be for both breakfast as well as dinner. This hotel really oozes with charm. The stairways, the atrium, the lobby, and the views out the window and over the balcony of the terrace restaurant really cannot be beat. If you stay anywhere else, you're making a mistake, because you will miss the feel of being in the middle of it all and in a building which is filled with charm. The location in the midst of the thousand palaces is also a must, in order to get the feel of the oppulence that once was Mexico City. One important caution though: DO NOT take advantage of the guided tours to the pyramids that can be arranged next to the front desk of the hotel. Either take a taxi or shop around. The pyramids are fantastic and must be seen, but the tour from the hotel is an absolute rip-off: they basically drove us around for half the day and made us wait in junky tourist shops, and then gave us only 60 minutes within which to tour the pyramids, which could easily be a 3 hour visit to enjoy it fully. 
