<Author>Brujitaann
<Content>Great location, but very little else I stayed at the Majestic on the recommendation of an old Bristish gentleman I'd met last year in Mexico City who had lunched at their famous Restaurante La Terraza there sometime during World War Two. He was very nostalgic about the experience. Sadly, I can't share his enthusiasm.The hotel was built in 1937, and time has not been kind to it. The lobby and atrium areas are attractive, as are the hallways with lovely Talavera tile embellishments, but the guest rooms and bathrooms are in dire need of a major renovation. They are shabby and dreary. One of the draperies in my room was hanging precariously. Hot water might or might not be available in the antiquated bathroom. The toilet might or might not flush (although the man with the plunger arrived promptly and solved the problem). The maid might or might not have remembered to place the promised coffee maker in the room, the in-room safe was broken, the clock blinked relentlessly, and the wiring is positively scary. The word firetrap kept floating to the surface of my mind, impinging on what little sleep I was able to get on the cement slab they called a bed, and what sounded either like construction noise or the vigorous activities of poltergeists in the next room didn't add to my feeling of delicious serentiy, especially when the noise continued far into the night.The Terrace Restaurant about which my British friend had spoken so tenderly has a spectacular view of the Zocalo, but that was all there was to recommend it. The food was mediocre, the service was poor and the prices were high. Despite the indifferent service in the dining room, the people at the reception desk and the bellhops who doubled as elevator operators were very pleasant indeed.I won't complain about the general noise as other reviewers have. Mexico City is the largest city in the world, and the Zocalo is one of the biggest squares extant, (second only to Red Square in Moscow, I seem to recall) so no reasonable person would expect it to be as quiet as an undiscovered tomb. A huge number of people congregate in the area around the incredibly beautiful Cathedral and they make a lot of noise. The traffic is non-stop and noisy. The are always sirens. Mysteriously, the Cathedral bells ring, but not when one would expect them to, and at 8:30 AM they begin a very interesting series of responsive rings, seven chimes each from what I guess is each of the bells in the two towers. The Cathedral has a great many bells, but it's a very big cathedral. The Mexican people are intensely patriotic, and there is a large gathering for the raising and lowering the gigantic flag (big enough to carpet Rhode Island) in great ceremonial style at 8:00 AM and again at 6:00 PM in the center of the Zocalo. The ceremony includes a band with plenty of drums and trumpets, soldiers, and military policemen. After the lowering of the flag in the evening, a group of Indians takes over the noise production duties and they drum the same rhythmic pattern far, far into the night. All this being said, I knew the Majestic would include plenty of ambiant city noise, just not construction workers or poltergeists.The hotel has an incredible view on the side facing the Zocalo, and the location is ideal for on-foot exploration of an endless number of fascinating places such as the Cathedral on the north side of the square and the National Palace directly across the square from the hotel which houses spectacular murals by Diego Rivera. About a block north of the National Palace are the ongoing excavations of an ancient Aztec temple, called Templo Mejor. The lovely museum, Palacio de Bellas Artes, is an easy walk about a mile north of the square.The area around the Cathedral presents an unforgettable shopping adventure for almost anything you can imagine. To compensate for the dreadful food at the Majestic, fine dining in the periphery of the Cathedral is a joyous adventure for the pushcart gourmet, and I loved every wonderful bite of everything I bought there. Another plus of eating near the Cathedral is the opportunity to observe a great number of fascinating people going about their daily lives.On my next visit to Mexico City, I intend to stay at the Hotel Catedral, which is a couple of blocks away because I love the central location, but sadly, I've enjoyed just about as much of the Majestic as I can stand. 
