<Content>Weekend on the Zocalo First of all, this hotel is at the heart of the city -- it sits right on the Zocalo, the 2nd largest (after Req Square) public square in the world. As you look out at the Zocalo, you're at the edge of Mexico's history -- the Templo Mayor of the Aztecs, the Spanish colonial cathedral, the swearing in of presidents, a few limited revolutions, and everything else that matters in Mexico.Second, it's well staffed, well run, efficient, and relatively friendly (for a big city hotel, in particular). It provides personalized attention if you need it, and the staff leaves you alone if that's what you want.The rooms are good value (not surprisingly, negotiable rates, especially during this New Depression). We were most recently there in June 2003.A suggestion: go for the weekend, when downtown is less crowded, and the air is markedly better (fewer cars downtown). Be sensible (don't wander around outside drunkenly, and don't take the green VW taxis) and enjoy being at the heart of a great City. 
